    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1607"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.77/93.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your confidential
                    despatch No. 19, of the 6th instant, in which you report a conversation between
                    yourself and Señor Obarrio, a member of the Panaman Assembly, in regard to the
                    proposed construction of the Panamá-David Railway.</p>
                <p>A copy of your despatch has been forwarded to the Secretary of War.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Note.</hi>—The President’s message to Congress on
                        departmental questions<note n="1" xml:id="d1607fn1">See <ref
                                target="#pg_467">page 467</ref> of this volume.</note> was read
                        December 21, 1911; it refers to the Panama Canal and calls attention to the
                        need for legislation relating to the government of the Canal Zone, which
                        should approximate a military government.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
